## Evaluating Agentic Workflows

### 1. The "Build First, Evaluate Later" Mindset

It is nearly impossible to anticipate every way an agent might fail.

- **Strategy:** Don't spend weeks predicting errors. Build a V1, run it, manually read outputs, spot weird behaviors.
- Once you spot a recurring error → build an "Eval" specifically to eliminate it.

### 2. The Two Types of Evaluation

| Type | When to Use | Example |
|---|---|---|
| **Objective Evals (Code-Based)** | Black-and-white rules | Python script counting competitor name mentions in output |
| **Subjective Evals (LLM-as-a-Judge)** | Qualitative outputs | Second LLM grading tone or depth of an essay |

> ⚠️ **Warning:** Asking an LLM to rate something "on a scale of 1 to 5" is often unreliable. More robust frameworks are required.

### 3. End-to-End vs. Component Evals

- **End-to-End Evals** — Measuring the final output of the entire system. *(Did it solve the customer's problem?)*
- **Component-Level Evals** — Measuring one specific micro-task. *(Did the routing LLM correctly identify a billing issue vs. tech support?)*

### 4. Error Analysis (Reading the "Traces")

When an agent fails, don't just look at the final bad answer. Perform **Error Analysis** by reading the **traces** — logs of intermediate steps, tool calls, and raw LLM thoughts — to pinpoint exactly which step in your decomposition failed.

